        <h1>LeetCode 3713: Minimum Cost to Make Arrays Identical (C++)</h1>

        <div class="problem-description">
            <p><strong>Problem:</strong>
                You are given two integer arrays arr and brr of the same length, and an integer k. You can perform the following operation any number of times: Select an index i where 0 &lt;= i &lt; arr.length, and update arr[i] to any integer value. The cost of this operation is abs(arr[i] - brr[i]) * k where arr[i] is the value before the operation. Return the minimum total cost to make arr identical to brr.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Example:</strong>
                Input: arr = [1,2,3,4], brr = [2,3,4,5], k = 1<br/>
                Output: 4<br/>
                Explanation: We can make arr identical to brr by updating each element with cost |1-2|*1 + |2-3|*1 + |3-4|*1 + |4-5|*1 = 4.<br/><br/>
                Input: arr = [5,10], brr = [5,10], k = 2<br/>
                Output: 0<br/>
                Explanation: Arrays are already identical.<br/><br/>
                Input: arr = [10,20,30], brr = [30,20,10], k = 5<br/>
                Output: 200<br/>
                Explanation: We can swap positions which costs less than direct updates.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="code-container">
            <button class="copy-button" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy Code</button>
            <pre><code class="language-cpp">class Solution {
public:
    long long minCost(vector&lt;int&gt;&amp; arr, vector&lt;int&gt;&amp; brr, long long k) {
        int n = arr.size();
        
        // Calculate direct cost of making each element identical
        long long directCost = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; n; i++) {
            directCost += (long long)abs(arr[i] - brr[i]) * k;
        }
        
        // Try rearranging: sort both arrays and match optimally
        vector&lt;int&gt; sortedArr = arr;
        vector&lt;int&gt; sortedBrr = brr;
        sort(sortedArr.begin(), sortedArr.end());
        sort(sortedBrr.begin(), sortedBrr.end());
        
        long long rearrangeCost = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; n; i++) {
            rearrangeCost += (long long)abs(sortedArr[i] - sortedBrr[i]) * k;
        }
        
        return min(directCost, rearrangeCost);
    }
};</code></pre>
